  {"t":"lead","html":"Beirut eats before it does almost anything else. This is a city where a hundred-year-old falafel counter and a two-seating chef's table sit four kilometers apart, where breakfast is a genuine destination, and where the table is still — whatever else is happening around it — the center of everything. Here's how to eat and move through it well."},
  {"t":"p","html":"Lebanese food doesn't really have a 'scene' so much as a rhythm: foul and hummus at dawn, manoushe mid-morning, mezze stretching across a whole evening, sweets whenever. Beirut does all of it, spread across neighborhoods with sharply different personalities. <strong>Hamra</strong>, Ras Beirut's bustling commercial spine around the American University of Beirut, is dense with breakfast counters and bookshop cafés and rarely quiet. <strong>Mar Mikhael</strong>, down by the water, turns into Beirut's liveliest bar strip after dark, its restaurants and grills feeding the same crowd. <strong>Gemmayzeh</strong>, one flight of stairs away — literally, the Saint Nicolas Stairs connect them — fills French-mandate-era buildings with bars, street art and a slightly calmer version of the same energy. Up the hill, <strong>Achrafieh</strong> is Beirut's elegant, red-roofed quarter, home to sweets shops and quieter, more refined tables. And across town, <strong>Bourj Hammoud</strong> — settled by Armenian refugees in the early twentieth century and still the heart of Armenian Beirut — has an entirely distinct food identity: basterma, soujouk, kebbe, a whole cured-meat and mezze culture you won't find in the same form anywhere else in the city."},
