  {"t":"warn","head":"Before you go","html":"Lebanon currently carries formal government travel advisories, and they're worth taking seriously — but they aren't uniform. Several governments currently draw a real distinction between Beirut and Mount Lebanon, generally urging caution there, and the south and border areas, which carry stronger warnings; a cessation of hostilities announced in spring 2026 has held, though both the US and UK describe the situation as fluid. Advisories are updated often and differ by country, so treat this paragraph as a starting point, not the final word. Check your own government's current, dated advisory — <strong>travel.state.gov</strong> for US citizens, <strong>gov.uk/foreign-travel-advice</strong> for UK citizens — before you book, and again closer to your trip, and consider registering with your embassy once you're there."},
  {"t":"tip","head":"Best time to visit","html":"<strong>April–June and September–October</strong> are the sweet spot — warm, dry and comfortable, good for both the coast and day trips. <strong>July–August</strong> is hot and the busiest, priciest season, as the diaspora comes home for summer. <strong>Winter</strong> is mild by regional standards, with occasional storms, and the cheapest hotel rates alongside November and March. Lebanon is often called the only country in the Levant with genuine four-season variation — a mild coast within an hour of snow in the mountains."},
